lign:left;">
There are 5 regular polyhedra - tetrahedron, hexahedron (cube), octahedron, dodecahedron and icosahedron.
<br /><br />
There is also a curious way that these 3-dimensional objects fit together. Starting
with a dodecahedron, fit around an icosahedron, so that the 20 vertices of the
dodecahedron meet the centre of the 20 faces of the icosahedron. Then build an
octahedron around the icosahedron so that the 12 vertices of the icosahedron meet
with the 12 edges of the octahedron (according to the golden section). Next build
a tetrahedron around the octahedron so that the 6 vertices of the octahedron meet
with the mid points of the 6 edges of the tetrahedron. Finally put a cube around
the tetrahedron so that the corners meet.
<br /><br />
Assuming that all 30 edges of the dodecahedron are 2 in length, and that all of
the polyhedra are regular. What is the length of the cube's edge?
<br /><br />
<p style="font-size:70%;">Final note: A big thanks to S0410N3 for helping to confirm the correct answer, and
for all his help to get this challenge ready.</p>

